{{Geo-term-stub}}

{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2015}} {{Use Irish English|date=March 2015}} {{Infobox University |name =Royal College of Science for Ireland |native_name = |image_name =Image:Irishgovbuildings.JPG |image_size = 300px |caption =The Royal College of Science building from 1911 to 1926; now [[Government Buildings]] |latin_name = |motto = |mottoeng = |established =1867 |closed =1926 |type =Public |affiliation = |endowment = |officer_in_charge = |chairman = |chancellor = |president = |vice-president = |superintendent = |provost = |vice_chancellor = |rector = |principal = |dean = |director = |head_label = |head = |faculty = |staff = |students = |undergrad = |postgrad = |doctoral = |other = |city =[[Dublin]] |state = |province = |country =Ireland (later [[Irish Free State]]) |coor = |campus = |former_names = |free_label = |free = |sports = |colors = |colours = |nickname = |mascot = |athletics = |affiliations = |website = |logo = |footnotes = }} The '''Royal College of Science for Ireland''' ('''RCScI'''<ref name="ucdrcsci">{{cite web|url=http://www.ucd.ie/merrionstreet/rcsci.html|title=The Royal College of Science for Ireland|year=2011|work=Merrion Street|publisher=UCD|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref>) was an institute for [[higher education]] in Dublin which existed from 1867 to 1926, specialising in [[physical sciences]] and [[applied science]]. It was originally based on [[St. Stephen's Green]], moving in 1911 to [[Government Buildings|a purpose-built "Royal College of Science" building]] on [[Merrion Street]]. In 1926 it was absorbed into [[University College Dublin]] (UCD) as the [[Faculty (division)|faculty]] of Science and Engineering.
==Foundation== The Museum of Economic Geology was founded by the [[Dublin Castle administration]] in 1845, with chemist [[Robert Kane (chemist)|Robert Kane]] as curator, and a focus on [[mining in Ireland]] similar to the [[Geological Museum|Museum of Practical Geology]] in London.<ref name="sc1864p9">Select Committee (1864) [http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/14615/page/380225 p.ix]</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museum.ie/en/exhibition/list/exhibition-details-outofstorage.aspx?article=5be165bf-d84b-4c9a-a83f-4473c71bea70|title=The Museum of Irish Industry|work=Permanent Exhibitions > Out of Storage|publisher=[[National Museum of Ireland]]|accessdate=16 February 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150216193808/http://www.museum.ie/en/exhibition/list/exhibition-details-outofstorage.aspx?article=5be165bf-d84b-4c9a-a83f-4473c71bea70|archivedate=16 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 1847, Kane was promoted to director, expanding its remit, and renaming it the [[Museum of Irish Industry]] (MII).<ref name="sc1864p9"/> In 1853 a new [[Science and Art Department]] was created within [[Government of the United Kingdom|the Whitehall administration]], and in 1854 the MII placed under its remit.<ref name="sc1864p14">Select Committee (1864) [http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/14615/page/380230 p.xiv]</ref> A School of Science applied to Mining and the Arts was created, modelled on the [[Royal School of Mines]] in London, with four professorships shared jointly by the MII school and the [[Royal Dublin Society]] (RDS).<ref name="sc1864p14"/> The MII and School shared premises at 51, St. Stephen's Green, acquired in 1846 and fitted out by 1852.<ref name="sc1864p9"/> In 1864, a [[select committee]] of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|UK parliament]] recommended that the MII and School be entirely separated from the RDS and broadened into a government-supported College of Science for Ireland.<ref>Select Committee (1864) [http://www.dippam.ac.uk/eppi/documents/14615/page/380239 p.xxiii §§5–8]</ref> In 1865, [[HM Treasury]] agreed and in 1867 a commission was appointed by the education committee of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]]. The commission, headed by [[William Parsons, 3rd Earl of Rosse]], outlined the scope and functions of the proposed college, and the RCScI mission statement on 11 September 1867 was:<ref name="ucdarch">{{cite web|url=http://www.ucd.ie/archives/html/university/rcsi.htm|title=Royal College of Science in Ireland|work=Archives|publisher=UCD|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> :The object of the Royal College of Science is to supply as far as practicable a Complete Course of instruction in Science applicable to the Industrial Arts, especially those which may be classed broadly under the heads of Mining, Agriculture, Engineering, and Manufactures, and to aid in the instruction of Teachers for the local Schools of Science
[[George Sigerson]] complained in 1868 that the RCScI was less open to Catholics than the MII had been.<ref>{{cite book |title=Modern Ireland: Its Vital Questions, Secret Societies, and Government |url=https://archive.org/details/modernirelandit00sigegoog |chapterurl=http://www.libraryireland.com/articles/ModIrelandRoyalCollege/index.php |year=1868 |publisher=Longmans, Green, Reader, and Dyer |location=London |pages=197–207 |chapter=The Royal College of Science for Ireland}}</ref>
==Later development== The RCScI's remit was later changed to exclude include agriculture and include "Physics and Natural Science".<ref name="ucdarch"/> The number of students enrolled increased gradually.<ref name="ivrla30371">{{cite web|url=http://digital.ucd.ie/view/ivrla:30371|title=RCSI numbers of attendence &#91;sic&#93;|date=1 December 2009|work=UCD Digital Library|publisher=UCD|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>
{|class="wikitable" |+ Students enrolled in RCScI day courses<ref name="ivrla30371"/> |- ! Year ending | 1869 || 1879 || 1889 || 1899 || 1909 || 1919 |- ! Number enrolled | 32 || 60 || 103 || 97 || 117 || 258 |}
By 1898 the RCScI had chairs of Mining and Mineralogy, Physics, Chemistry, Zoology, Botany, Geology, Applied Mathematics and Mechanism, Descriptive Geometry and Engineering.<ref name="ucdarch"/> In 1900, control was transferred from the Science and Art Department in London to the Department of Agriculture and Technical Instruction in Dublin, headed by [[Horace Plunkett]].<ref name="ucdrcsci"/> A new building was proposed in 1897 and a site from [[Merrion Street]] to [[Kildare Street]] was chosen in 1898; in 1899 the plan was extended to include government administrative offices as well as the new college.<ref name="ucdnewbldg">{{cite web|url=http://www.ucd.ie/merrionstreet/newbuilding.html|title=The New Building|year=2011|work=Merrion Street|publisher=UCD|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> The new building was designed by Sir [[Aston Webb]]; the [[foundation stone]] was laid in 1904 by [[Edward VII]] and it was opened in 1911 by [[George V]].<ref name="ucdnewbldg"/>
In 1926 the RCScI was absorbed into UCD where it became the UCD Science and Engineering faculties. Science moved to [[National Concert Hall|UCD's Earlsfort Terrace building]], and on to [[Belfield, Dublin|Belfield]] in the 1960s; Engineering moved from Merrion Street to Belfield in 1989. The RCScI building was then absorbed into [[Government Buildings]] with the rest of Aston Webb's complex, lavishly renovated by [[Charles Haughey]] and used to house the [[Department of the Taoiseach]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.taoiseach.gov.ie/eng/Historical_Information/History_of_Government_Buildings/|title=History of Government Buildings: 1904-1922 and 1990|publisher=Department of the Taoiseach|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref>
